00:22:33.501 --> 00:22:35.667
Maybe that's just
my group of friends.

00:22:35.667 --> 00:22:37.234
But when you're
developing this product,

00:22:37.234 --> 00:22:40.701
it may be a simple app
that only requires you.

00:22:40.701 --> 00:22:41.968
And you may just
need some icons

00:22:41.968 --> 00:22:44.033
that you can source
from creative commons,

00:22:44.033 --> 00:22:47.267
and use Microsoft Paint
to knock up

00:22:47.267 --> 00:22:49.300
some basic graphics and convert
into pngs or whatever,

00:22:49.300 --> 00:22:50.601
but chances are
you're gonna need

00:22:50.601 --> 00:22:52.334
to invest in a designer
at some point.

00:22:52.334 --> 00:22:53.701
And also,
once your team grows,

00:22:53.701 --> 00:22:55.167
if it becomes a really
big application,

00:22:55.167 --> 00:22:58.167
you're gonna need someone
to manage these costs.

00:22:58.167 --> 00:22:59.968
Now with development
of any code--

00:22:59.968 --> 00:23:02.067
I was having a chat with
a couple of people last night,

00:23:02.067 --> 00:23:04.234
and we were saying
there's an 80-20-80 rule.

00:23:04.234 --> 00:23:05.501
I don't know how many
of you have heard this.

00:23:05.501 --> 00:23:06.801
You probably know it

00:23:06.801 --> 00:23:08.501
even if you haven't heard it
explained like this.

00:23:08.501 --> 00:23:10.334
And it's the idea
that 80% of the development

00:23:10.334 --> 00:23:12.367
will take 80%
of the time,

00:23:12.367 --> 00:23:15.701
and the last 20% will take
another 80% of the time.

00:23:15.701 --> 00:23:18.167
Because you're, you know,
you get nearly there,

00:23:18.167 --> 00:23:19.267
and then you're like,
"Oh, what if we just moved that?

00:23:19.267 --> 00:23:20.501
"And hey, that bit
doesn't work.

00:23:20.501 --> 00:23:22.400
And oh, we just need
to change that around."

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:25.634
Feature creep--what if we
added this element?

00:23:25.634 --> 00:23:27.501
So think about that too.

00:23:27.501 --> 00:23:31.167
But one of the things also
to think about is iterate often.

00:23:31.167 --> 00:23:32.601
At Google we roll stuff out.

00:23:32.601 --> 00:23:34.701
It's why we have the beta tag
on so many products.

00:23:34.701 --> 00:23:36.000
But we want to get
stuff out there,

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.200
and we want to see
how people are using it.

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:39.968
And I've seen
big organizations

00:23:39.968 --> 00:23:41.734
that I've talked to
crippled by meetings.

00:23:41.734 --> 00:23:43.734
They want to get
everything perfect,

00:23:43.734 --> 00:23:46.167
so they wait a year and a half
before launching something,

00:23:46.167 --> 00:23:48.000
by which time it's
kind of obsolete anyway,

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:49.100
especially on the Internet,

00:23:49.100 --> 00:23:51.300
and especially
in social networking.

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:53.400
So think about creating
a small feature set

00:23:53.400 --> 00:23:56.167
that solves a real problem,
get it out the door quickly,

00:23:56.167 --> 00:23:59.667
see what users think, and then
iterate, fix it, update.

00:23:59.667 --> 00:24:03.567
Here's an example
of an application from iGoogle.

00:24:03.567 --> 00:24:07.000
It just shows a really nice way
to solve a user problem.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:08.901
All of you have probably
at one time or another

00:24:08.901 --> 00:24:11.534
needed to search
online for travel.

00:24:11.534 --> 00:24:13.434
If you just know that you
want to visit a friend--

00:24:13.434 --> 00:24:15.334
Let's say
I'm in San Francisco

00:24:15.334 --> 00:24:16.667
and I've got a friend
in L.A.,

00:24:16.667 --> 00:24:18.934
and I want to visit them
sometime in June.

00:24:18.934 --> 00:24:22.100
I don't necessarily
want to search 34 or 30 times--

00:24:22.100 --> 00:24:25.000
31 times for all
the different days

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:26.968
to find
the cheapest flight.

00:24:26.968 --> 00:24:28.767
I install this gadget,
and I say I want to travel

00:24:28.767 --> 00:24:30.334
from here to here
in this month--Save.

00:24:30.334 --> 00:24:31.767
And then I don't know
if you can see it,

00:24:31.767 --> 00:24:34.033
but the cheapest flights
are outlined in yellow.

00:24:34.033 --> 00:24:36.200
And every time I come back
or reload this page,

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:37.934
that's gonna do
a real-time search

00:24:37.934 --> 00:24:39.634
and show
the cheapest dates.

00:24:39.634 --> 00:24:41.467
And so instead of me
having to, you know,

00:24:41.467 --> 00:24:42.601
go and do these
searches every day

00:24:42.601 --> 00:24:43.767
or subscribe
to something,

00:24:43.767 --> 00:24:46.400
I just stick this gadget
on my homepage

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:47.968
and it's giving me
the information I want.

00:24:47.968 --> 00:24:49.701
It's kind of like
a personal search agent,

00:24:49.701 --> 00:24:51.767
if that's what you want
to think about.

00:24:51.767 --> 00:24:53.934
This doesn't necessarily
make a lot of sense socially,

00:24:53.934 --> 00:24:55.501
but these are the sort of things
you want to be thinking about.

00:24:55.501 --> 00:24:56.734
Does this solve user need?

00:24:56.734 --> 00:24:58.400
Does this do something
users are gonna

00:24:58.400 --> 00:25:01.767
find useful
and want to engage with?

00:25:01.767 --> 00:25:03.934
Next, hosting
and operations.

00:25:03.934 --> 00:25:06.501
Does everyone know
what "LAMP" stands for?

00:25:06.501 --> 00:25:07.601
Okay, a few don't.

00:25:07.601 --> 00:25:10.734
It's Linux, Apache,
MySQL, and PHP.

00:25:10.734 --> 00:25:13.400
It's just a name for a kind of
server with some software on it.

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:16.200
It could be Windows, IIS,
SQL Server, and .Net,

00:25:16.200 --> 00:25:18.834
but WISN is probably
not as easy to say.

00:25:18.834 --> 00:25:21.000
I mean, it could be Linux,
Apache, Postgres, and JSP,

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.434
but again, LAPJ doesn't really
make a lot of sense.

00:25:23.434 --> 00:25:25.100
The point is it's
having some servers

00:25:25.100 --> 00:25:26.968
with some software on
that you manage.

00:25:26.968 --> 00:25:28.968
Either you own those servers
or you're leasing them

00:25:28.968 --> 00:25:30.901
in a data center somewhere.

00:25:30.901 --> 00:25:33.300
And that's gonna have
a cost associated with it.

00:25:33.300 --> 00:25:35.534
Not only the cost of actually
hiring the hardware,

00:25:35.534 --> 00:25:37.501
but then you're gonna need
sys admin skills.

00:25:37.501 --> 00:25:38.667
You're gonna need
to make sure

00:25:38.667 --> 00:25:40.200
that your server software
is patched.

00:25:40.200 --> 00:25:41.868
I don't know how many of you
went to Matt Cutts's talk

00:25:41.868 --> 00:25:44.734
about building
a good Web site,

00:25:44.734 --> 00:25:46.100
but one of the points
he made was, you know,

00:25:46.100 --> 00:25:47.567
Web sites now--it's PCs.

00:25:47.567 --> 00:25:49.801
Home PCs become more secure
as people switch to Apple,

00:25:49.801 --> 00:25:51.033
as Windows 7 rolls out,

00:25:51.033 --> 00:25:53.033
as people are starting
to use Linux.

00:25:53.033 --> 00:25:55.267
The hackers are going
off the Web sites

00:25:55.267 --> 00:25:56.834
because they're
easier to attack.

00:25:56.834 --> 00:25:59.634
People don't necessarily patch
Apache to the latest version,

00:25:59.634 --> 00:26:01.901
and then there'll be
vulnerabilities.

00:26:01.901 --> 00:26:04.067
So if you're running
your own servers,

00:26:04.067 --> 00:26:05.734
you need to make sure
they're up to date.

00:26:05.734 --> 00:26:08.734
And there's a cost there too.
Don't forget about that cost.

00:26:08.734 --> 00:26:12.501
Joyent and Sun off
a kind of hosted platform.

00:26:12.501 --> 00:26:15.968
That's scalable, that runs
for free for very low usage

00:26:15.968 --> 00:26:19.767
up to cost once you start
to get a bit of traffic,

00:26:19.767 --> 00:26:23.000
and it's on demand, so you can
scale them up and down.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:26.067
Some of you may know
of Amazon EC2.

00:26:26.067 --> 00:26:28.834
They basically let you
rent machines--virtual machines,

00:26:28.834 --> 00:26:30.267
and you build
an image and install it,

00:26:30.267 --> 00:26:32.033
but again you'll need
to think about sys admin

00:26:32.033 --> 00:26:34.234
and patching
and all that good stuff.

00:26:34.234 --> 00:26:38.801
They recently launched,
I think last week, on the 18th,

00:26:38.801 --> 00:26:40.868
a system that allows you
to auto-scale based on demand,

00:26:40.868 --> 00:26:43.501
so they just deploy
new servers as you need it.

00:26:43.501 --> 00:26:46.267
But you're still having to
provision the software yourself.

00:26:46.267 --> 00:26:47.601
Now I don't want
to sit here and go,

00:26:47.601 --> 00:26:48.934
"Well, Google have got
the solution for you,"

00:26:48.934 --> 00:26:50.133
'cause that's not
what this is about,

00:26:50.133 --> 00:26:51.901
but if I were
a developer in this age,

00:26:51.901 --> 00:26:53.167
I'd be looking at App Engine

00:26:53.167 --> 00:26:54.634
or something similar
pretty seriously.

00:26:54.634 --> 00:26:57.167
Because App Engine lets you
focus just on the software.

00:26:57.167 --> 00:26:58.400
You build the software,

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:00.667
Google takes care
of scaling it up and down.

00:27:00.667 --> 00:27:03.868
And remember,
with social applications,

00:27:03.868 --> 00:27:05.200
things can go viral
very quickly.

00:27:05.200 --> 00:27:07.968
You get a few key people
who are interested in your app,

00:27:07.968 --> 00:27:09.467
they tell their friends,
and suddenly bang,

00:27:09.467 --> 00:27:11.100
you've got a million users,
it can happen.

00:27:11.100 --> 00:27:13.601
Here's a graph of growth.

00:27:13.601 --> 00:27:16.734
It's pretty simplistic, but it
should give you a basic idea.

00:27:16.734 --> 00:27:19.367
If you're using a LAMP stack,
if you're renting machines,

00:27:19.367 --> 00:27:20.934
your machines are gonna
be good to a certain point,

00:27:20.934 --> 00:27:22.467
and then you're gonna need
to deploy additional ones.

00:27:22.467 --> 00:27:24.801
So you're really gonna see
this step growth graph.

00:27:24.801 --> 00:27:26.133
And something
to think about there

00:27:26.133 --> 00:27:28.467
is if load
diminishes over time,

00:27:28.467 --> 00:27:30.067
how do you take
those servers offline?

00:27:30.067 --> 00:27:31.334
You're still gonna
be paying rental,

00:27:31.334 --> 00:27:32.567
and chances are
you're gonna be

00:27:32.567 --> 00:27:34.300
in for a minimum
contract period.

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:37.200
So think carefully
about buying new servers.

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:39.067
EC2 lets you scale
a little more smoothly.

00:27:39.067 --> 00:27:42.000
You can switch them
on and off as load requires.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.968
App Engine's a slightly
smoother graph.

00:27:44.968 --> 00:27:46.234
I don't want to sit here
and push App Engine,

00:27:46.234 --> 00:27:48.033
but because you're just
focusing on process,

00:27:48.033 --> 00:27:50.100
you're literally only
paying for what you use.

00:27:50.100 --> 00:27:51.501
The other advantage
of App Engine is you'll get

00:27:51.501 --> 00:27:53.767
up to five million page views
a month for free.

00:27:53.767 --> 00:27:56.701
So they'll let you experiment
with different services

00:27:56.701 --> 00:27:58.167
and see if your
business is viable

00:27:58.167 --> 00:28:01.901
before you actually have to
start paying hosting costs.

00:28:01.901 --> 00:28:03.534
There are a bunch
of talks on App Engine

00:28:03.534 --> 00:28:04.634
if you want to learn more,

00:28:04.634 --> 00:28:06.234
and there's some
office hours happening

00:28:06.234 --> 00:28:07.868
if you really want
to play grab the SDK,

00:28:07.868 --> 00:28:10.601
have a knock around, that's not
what we're here to talk about.

00:28:10.601 --> 00:28:12.934
Marketing and advertising.
So advertising.

00:28:12.934 --> 00:28:15.234
You've built your application,
you want to get it known.

00:28:15.234 --> 00:28:16.334
There's a few ways
to do this.

00:28:16.334 --> 00:28:18.734
Obviously AdWords--

00:28:18.734 --> 00:28:22.067
paid networks where you can
advertise your application--

00:28:22.067 --> 00:28:24.100
but then actually within
the social networks as well.

00:28:24.100 --> 00:28:27.067
You can do gallery sponsorship,
as Gerardo mentioned,

00:28:27.067 --> 00:28:29.000
there are even some ways
to get your app

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:30.334
sponsored in exchange
for rev share,

00:28:30.334 --> 00:28:32.834
you know, get it featured
in gallery listings.

00:28:32.834 --> 00:28:34.000
There are app
ad networks too,

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:35.567
so you can advertise
within other apps,

00:28:35.567 --> 00:28:37.133
you can advertise
on the social networks,

00:28:37.133 --> 00:28:39.367
you can advertise in places
where people would go,

00:28:39.367 --> 00:28:41.100
and advertise
in areas where people

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:42.434
actually engage
in what you're doing.

00:28:42.434 --> 00:28:46.167
So if you're building
a virtual dog application,

00:28:46.167 --> 00:28:48.000
go to pet sites
and say, you know,

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.367
if you're thinking
about buying a dog,

00:28:49.367 --> 00:28:51.234
why not try the app first to see
if you can look after one?

00:28:51.234 --> 00:28:53.200
There's no real, kind of,
you know, parallel to draw,

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:54.868
but people who like dogs
in real life

00:28:54.868 --> 00:28:56.734
probably like
virtual dogs too.

00:28:56.734 --> 00:28:59.133
So think
about that as well.

00:28:59.133 --> 00:29:01.200
Then you've got
organic growth.

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:03.667
So within the social network,
you've got a bunch of mechanisms

00:29:03.667 --> 00:29:05.567
for talking to people.

00:29:05.567 --> 00:29:06.767
You've got activity streams,

00:29:06.767 --> 00:29:08.100
so when someone
installs an application

00:29:08.100 --> 00:29:10.000
you can write to that
and advertise the fact.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:13.667
You've got installing the
application on a user's profile.

00:29:13.667 --> 00:29:15.634
You can send invitations out.

00:29:15.634 --> 00:29:18.033
But be smart
about sending invitations.

00:29:18.033 --> 00:29:19.434
One of the things
that really upsets me

00:29:19.434 --> 00:29:22.000
about applications
I see today is I install one,

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.868
and it says, "Send an invitation
to all your friends."

00:29:24.868 --> 00:29:26.801
Probably most of my friends
aren't gonna like

00:29:26.801 --> 00:29:28.634
the same applications
that I do.

00:29:28.634 --> 00:29:30.634
And applications
have the ability

00:29:30.634 --> 00:29:32.300
to learn about my friends.

00:29:32.300 --> 00:29:33.667
Especially in OpenSocial.

00:29:33.667 --> 00:29:35.834
I can poll my friends,
learn about their interests,

00:29:35.834 --> 00:29:38.000
so if I'm installing
a snowboarding application,

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:39.701
instead of just saying,
"Give this to all my friends,"

00:29:39.701 --> 00:29:42.133
why not find out which of my
friends also like snowboarding?

00:29:42.133 --> 00:29:43.534
And then intelligently say,

00:29:43.534 --> 00:29:45.400
"Hey, we see five of your
friends are also snowboarders,

00:29:45.400 --> 00:29:47.234
"do you think they'd
like this app too?

00:29:47.234 --> 00:29:48.601
Click here to send
an invite."

00:29:48.601 --> 00:29:51.334
It's a lot friendlier,
and users are gonna

00:29:51.334 --> 00:29:53.400
feel like your app's
a bit smarter,

00:29:53.400 --> 00:29:55.300
and that it's actually something
they'd want to pass on.

00:29:55.300 --> 00:29:58.033
And then of course
notifications.

00:29:58.033 --> 00:29:59.534
Once you install the app
or do something

00:29:59.534 --> 00:30:02.267
You can write to your wall, or
write to your activity stream,

00:30:02.267 --> 00:30:05.267
or, you know, send out mails,
or whatever it might be.

00:30:05.267 --> 00:30:08.868
But it's not just within
the social network itself.

00:30:08.868 --> 00:30:14.868
BuddyPoke is the most popular
application on OpenSocial.

00:30:14.868 --> 00:30:17.634
And there's about 3 1/2 thousand
videos on YouTube,

00:30:17.634 --> 00:30:19.767
and they're all kind of,
you know, a few thousand views,

00:30:19.767 --> 00:30:21.267
but even if each of them
were only 1,000,

00:30:21.267 --> 00:30:25.200
that's still, what, 3 1/2
million views of BuddyPoke.

00:30:25.200 --> 00:30:28.167
And if you are gonna put videos
of your content up on YouTube,

00:30:28.167 --> 00:30:29.534
think about the metadata.

00:30:29.534 --> 00:30:31.667
See in the red box? "Buddy Poke,
Buddy Poke, Buddy Poke..."

00:30:31.667 --> 00:30:33.567
Sure, if you search for "Buddy
Poke," that's the first result.

00:30:33.567 --> 00:30:36.000
Simply because they
cracked the metadata.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:37.567
But how many people
search for Buddy Poke?

00:30:37.567 --> 00:30:39.267
Probably not that many.

00:30:39.267 --> 00:30:40.634
Think about what
your application is,

00:30:40.634 --> 00:30:41.834
don't just put the name,

00:30:41.834 --> 00:30:43.901
but also put the types
of things that it is.

00:30:43.901 --> 00:30:45.801
So if it's a virtual pet app,
don't put, you know,

00:30:45.801 --> 00:30:48.367
"My V-Pet."
Put "virtual pet."

00:30:48.367 --> 00:30:51.701
You know,
"play with your dog online."

00:30:51.701 --> 00:30:53.133
Community management.
This is the next one.

00:30:53.133 --> 00:30:55.634
So you've got, you know,
100,000 users,

00:30:55.634 --> 00:30:58.167
and some of them are gonna
start breaking things,

00:30:58.167 --> 00:30:59.701
so you need to think
about security issues.

00:30:59.701 --> 00:31:02.634
Some of them are just
gonna be stupid.

00:31:02.634 --> 00:31:04.133
You know, users are dumb.

00:31:04.133 --> 00:31:07.033
Not every user, but guarantee,
lowest common denominator.

00:31:07.033 --> 00:31:08.734
My mom hitting
your application

00:31:08.734 --> 00:31:11.067
is gonna click in the wrong
place every single time,

00:31:11.067 --> 00:31:12.634
and bookmark places
that you didn't expect

00:31:12.634 --> 00:31:13.767
after submitting a form

00:31:13.767 --> 00:31:15.601
with something weird
in a query string,

00:31:15.601 --> 00:31:16.934
so that when she comes
back to that bookmark

00:31:16.934 --> 00:31:18.334
it breaks something.

00:31:18.334 --> 00:31:20.000
And it's something
you haven't thought about.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:21.534
So you're gonna want
to test all this stuff.

00:31:21.534 --> 00:31:23.200
But you're also gonna
want to make sure

00:31:23.200 --> 00:31:27.167
there's a feedback loop for
your users to report problems.

00:31:27.167 --> 00:31:28.868
The cool thing is because
of social networks,

00:31:28.868 --> 00:31:32.400
you can actually leverage users
who are using your apps

00:31:32.400 --> 00:31:34.334
and recruit power users
to help support.

00:31:34.334 --> 00:31:35.767
You know, people who actually
enjoy playing with it

00:31:35.767 --> 00:31:37.033
and have a bit
of time to spare

00:31:37.033 --> 00:31:38.667
and are really happy
to give their time.

00:31:38.667 --> 00:31:40.601
With the inclusion
of virtual currency,

00:31:40.601 --> 00:31:42.067
maybe you can reward them.

00:31:42.067 --> 00:31:43.834
So with the Mouse Hunt game,
people who are, you know,

00:31:43.834 --> 00:31:45.234
happy to support your forums

00:31:45.234 --> 00:31:47.501
with users who are
having install issues,

00:31:47.501 --> 00:31:50.200
maybe chuck them a few pieces
of gold or a new bit of cheese

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:52.200
every time they help
someone out effectively.

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:53.367
It's a really nice
way to do it,

00:31:53.367 --> 00:31:55.934
it's not costing
you anything overtly,

00:31:55.934 --> 00:32:00.567
but it's recruiting a great
bunch of people to help you out.

00:32:00.567 --> 00:32:03.267
And scale by
leveraging your users.

00:32:03.267 --> 00:32:04.934
So also forums.

00:32:04.934 --> 00:32:07.234
Where people can actually
post these messages.

00:32:07.234 --> 00:32:08.567
Most social networks
will have

00:32:08.567 --> 00:32:10.467
a discussion area
that you can use.

00:32:10.467 --> 00:32:12.000
But there are things
like Google Groups

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:14.100
where you can set up
free discussion forums too,

00:32:14.100 --> 00:32:16.801
if that's what
you want to do.

00:32:16.801 --> 00:32:21.167
Now, other costs.
Ad sales.

00:32:21.167 --> 00:32:23.234
You've got some ads
running on your application.

00:32:23.234 --> 00:32:25.868
Maybe your application's
become so popular

00:32:25.868 --> 00:32:27.300
the ad network
you were using

00:32:27.300 --> 00:32:28.767
can't actually
deliver inventory.

00:32:28.767 --> 00:32:31.167
After a certain point, you know,
ads just stop showing.

00:32:31.167 --> 00:32:32.634
So you're gonna
have to either find

00:32:32.634 --> 00:32:34.100
a manual
or an automated solution

00:32:34.100 --> 00:32:35.634
that lets you switch
ad networks,

00:32:35.634 --> 00:32:38.367
possibly multiple times a day,
if your app's really popular.

00:32:38.367 --> 00:32:40.300
This is something
to think about early on

00:32:40.300 --> 00:32:42.567
so that you're ready
when it happens.

00:32:42.567 --> 00:32:43.567
Direct sales force.

00:32:43.567 --> 00:32:44.734
Maybe it gets to the point

00:32:44.734 --> 00:32:46.567
where you have built
this $100-million app,

00:32:46.567 --> 00:32:48.100
and you want to have
a direct sales force

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:50.501
who are ringing people up to
advertise specifically with you.

00:32:50.501 --> 00:32:52.501
Again these are costs
you need to think about.

00:32:52.501 --> 00:32:53.701
One of the cool things
about salespeople, though,

00:32:53.701 --> 00:32:55.067
is they work for commission.

00:32:55.067 --> 00:32:57.701
So you can only pay them
if they're really successful.

00:32:57.701 --> 00:33:00.367
But it's still gonna be
a cost that's associated.

00:33:00.367 --> 00:33:01.567
Rev sharing, partnerships.

00:33:01.567 --> 00:33:02.968
If you're using
something like AdSense,

00:33:02.968 --> 00:33:04.300
don't forget a chunk
of money

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:07.167
will actually go to
the network providing the ads.

00:33:07.167 --> 00:33:08.934
On fixed costs--
office, legal.

00:33:08.934 --> 00:33:10.267
So if you're
renting offices,

00:33:10.267 --> 00:33:11.934
don't forget rent
is a pretty big deal.

00:33:11.934 --> 00:33:14.133
Electricity,
things like that. Tax.

00:33:14.133 --> 00:33:16.467
But more importantly
legal costs.

00:33:16.467 --> 00:33:18.133
This is a social network
application you're building.

00:33:18.133 --> 00:33:21.434
You're gonna be
interacting with user data.

00:33:21.434 --> 00:33:23.133
The moment
you start to do that

00:33:23.133 --> 00:33:26.200
you want to have
a rock-solid privacy policy.

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:27.567
You want to make it
absolutely clear

00:33:27.567 --> 00:33:28.968
what the terms
of service are,

00:33:28.968 --> 00:33:30.767
what you're gonna be doing
with peoples' data.

00:33:30.767 --> 00:33:32.634
You can try
and write this yourself.

00:33:32.634 --> 00:33:34.234
You might be
very successful,

00:33:34.234 --> 00:33:36.300
or you might get sued because
you didn't make it clear

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:38.434
what was happening or
the language wasn't appropriate.

00:33:38.434 --> 00:33:40.767
One of the best things
you can do early on

00:33:40.767 --> 00:33:43.033
is invest a little bit
of money in getting

00:33:43.033 --> 00:33:46.300
a rock-solid legal disclaimer
or, you know, terms of service.

00:33:46.300 --> 00:33:47.834
From a professional.

00:33:47.834 --> 00:33:49.234
Make sure it's
from a professional.

00:33:49.234 --> 00:33:50.667
That's absolutely key.

00:33:50.667 --> 00:33:52.534
Tracking and optimizing.

00:33:52.534 --> 00:33:54.000
So they talked a little bit
about this earlier,

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:58.567
but you want to look
at what your users are doing.

00:33:58.567 --> 00:34:02.200
I speak to so many big companies
in the UK and across Europe

00:34:02.200 --> 00:34:04.067
who have analytics
tools installed,

00:34:04.067 --> 00:34:05.634
and then you say, "Okay, so
how many users are you getting?"

00:34:05.634 --> 00:34:07.133
They'll turn around
and go,

00:34:07.133 --> 00:34:09.634
"Oh, we don't really know.
We don't look at the data."

00:34:09.634 --> 00:34:10.934
You're recording it.
It's there.

00:34:10.934 --> 00:34:12.100
That's actually
information

00:34:12.100 --> 00:34:13.534
about who's coming
to your Web site.

00:34:13.534 --> 00:34:15.801
If you're not looking
at this stuff every single day,

00:34:15.801 --> 00:34:17.133
you're missing a trick.

00:34:17.133 --> 00:34:19.567
This is a real-time
kind of health check.

00:34:19.567 --> 00:34:22.200
Pulse of who's interacting
with your Web site,

00:34:22.200 --> 00:34:24.367
or in this case,
your social application.

00:34:24.367 --> 00:34:27.300
So record data,
look at it, and react to it.

00:34:27.300 --> 00:34:28.701
If people are clicking
on the wrong button,

00:34:28.701 --> 00:34:30.968
if they're going through
the wrong path to get somewhere,

00:34:30.968 --> 00:34:32.567
it may be the fact that
your users are just clumsy

00:34:32.567 --> 00:34:34.100
and don't know
what they're doing,

00:34:34.100 --> 00:34:36.667
but it could also be possible
that it's not entirely clear.

00:34:36.667 --> 00:34:38.601
You know, we can sometimes
be so close to our apps

00:34:38.601 --> 00:34:40.968
that it seems really obvious
what people should be doing.

00:34:40.968 --> 00:34:42.300
A user comes in
from nowhere,

00:34:42.300 --> 00:34:43.834
clicks on things
that you just didn't expect,

00:34:43.834 --> 00:34:46.300
and ends up in a terrible,
terrible mess.

00:34:46.300 --> 00:34:48.701
So make sure that you're
monitoring this stuff too.

00:34:48.701 --> 00:34:50.968
Also test
different solutions.

00:34:50.968 --> 00:34:53.767
At Google, for Google Search,
at any given time,

00:34:53.767 --> 00:34:55.567
we have five to ten
experiments

00:34:55.567 --> 00:34:57.167
going on for
our search results.

00:34:57.167 --> 00:34:58.501
And I think we deployed
something like

00:34:58.501 --> 00:35:01.467
250 changes to our
search results last year.

00:35:01.467 --> 00:35:02.667
So we're always trying
to tweak

00:35:02.667 --> 00:35:04.501
just a little bit
to make things better.

00:35:04.501 --> 00:35:05.868
And whenever
you're thinking

00:35:05.868 --> 00:35:07.601
about building a Web site
or building an application,

00:35:07.601 --> 00:35:09.167
you should be thinking
about this too.

00:35:09.167 --> 00:35:10.334
I'm not suggesting you get

00:35:10.334 --> 00:35:11.868
that aggressive
with the number of changes,

00:35:11.868 --> 00:35:15.100
but I guarantee whatever you
launch isn't the best it can be.

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:18.367
So you should always be
looking for better solutions.

00:35:18.367 --> 00:35:24.367
With that said,
we're on to best practices.

00:35:24.367 --> 00:35:27.968
Capiel: I think Chewy
mentioned it quite a bit,

00:35:27.968 --> 00:35:30.167
and I just want
to really bring this home

00:35:30.167 --> 00:35:33.200
that you got to measure
and you got to optimize

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:34.667
what you're doing.

00:35:34.667 --> 00:35:38.801
And there's really kind of three
key metrics at a high level

00:35:38.801 --> 00:35:39.968
that you're gonna
be looking at.

00:35:39.968 --> 00:35:41.968
First is reach,

00:35:41.968 --> 00:35:46.434
which is how many people are
you able to reach and acquire?

00:35:46.434 --> 00:35:47.767
Then there's retention,

00:35:47.767 --> 00:35:50.234
so you've gotten a user
into your application.

00:35:50.234 --> 00:35:52.968
How often can you get them
to use the application

00:35:52.968 --> 00:35:54.133
and stay in there?

00:35:54.133 --> 00:35:56.067
So how often you
get 'em to come back,

00:35:56.067 --> 00:35:57.901
and how long
do you keep them for?

00:35:57.901 --> 00:36:01.367
And then finally if you do
a great job of those first two,

00:36:01.367 --> 00:36:03.400
then I would
highly encourage you

00:36:03.400 --> 00:36:06.267
to pay a lot of attention
to the next piece, which is--

00:36:06.267 --> 00:36:08.167
okay, I got all these users,
they're coming back,

00:36:08.167 --> 00:36:10.367
now how do I turn 'em
into dollars?

00:36:10.367 --> 00:36:13.300
And as you can see
from the ranges on this slide,

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:17.667
there tend to be pretty wide
ranges in terms of, you know,

00:36:17.667 --> 00:36:21.000
your ability
to convert users,

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:24.100
to acquire them,
and then also your ability

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:28.400
to take users
and make them active users.

00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:30.033
And Google Analytics,
by the way,

00:36:30.033 --> 00:36:31.400
is a great tool for that.

00:36:31.400 --> 00:36:34.834
Looking at bounce rates
on your application is good,

00:36:34.834 --> 00:36:37.734
looking at time spent
on your application is good.

00:36:37.734 --> 00:36:39.834
Those are key metrics
that you want to look at

00:36:39.834 --> 00:36:42.100
in terms of determining
whether you have

00:36:42.100 --> 00:36:44.767
a return problem
or an acquisition problem.

00:36:44.767 --> 00:36:48.567
So what are the communication
channels that you can use?

00:36:48.567 --> 00:36:51.601
Well, Chewy talked
a little bit about those.

00:36:51.601 --> 00:36:54.234
There's activity streams,
and there's notifications,

00:36:54.234 --> 00:36:58.400
and those depend quite a bit
in terms of the social network

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:00.834
about how they're
actually implemented,

00:37:00.834 --> 00:37:02.400
but almost all
the social networks

00:37:02.400 --> 00:37:05.000
have those
two basic channels.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:06.868
The key is,
to these channels--

00:37:06.868 --> 00:37:08.200
they can be very powerful,

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:11.367
but they can also be
very detrimental to your app.

00:37:11.367 --> 00:37:14.100
Like in the case
of Myspace,

00:37:14.100 --> 00:37:16.767
a notification is not only
a way that you can get someone

00:37:16.767 --> 00:37:18.467
to reengage with
your application,

00:37:18.467 --> 00:37:19.634
but it's also a way
that you can

00:37:19.634 --> 00:37:21.467
get 'em to uninstall
your application

00:37:21.467 --> 00:37:22.834
if you're spamming them.

00:37:22.834 --> 00:37:26.734
So the key to not spam,

00:37:26.734 --> 00:37:29.701
or to make your messages
actually relevant

00:37:29.701 --> 00:37:32.601
and not perceived as spam,
is to do a lot of testing.

00:37:32.601 --> 00:37:35.567
And A/B testing is
a very common technique

00:37:35.567 --> 00:37:36.634
where you're gonna be
testing

00:37:36.634 --> 00:37:38.400
different types
of dynamic content,

00:37:38.400 --> 00:37:42.334
you're gonna test
different types of offers,

00:37:42.334 --> 00:37:46.934
different pieces of content
that you consider relevant.

00:37:46.934 --> 00:37:51.801
For an A/B test you're gonna
want to typically use

00:37:51.801 --> 00:37:53.367
some type of analytics tool.

00:37:53.367 --> 00:37:56.334
Kontagent provides
some great analytic tools

00:37:56.334 --> 00:37:58.167
for doing A/B testing.

00:37:58.167 --> 00:37:59.601
But there's really--

00:37:59.601 --> 00:38:01.067
also a lot of people have
homegrown tools,

00:38:01.067 --> 00:38:02.834
and you can even use
Google Analytics

00:38:02.834 --> 00:38:04.834
for doing some of this.

00:38:04.834 --> 00:38:06.834
The interesting thing
about A/B testing

00:38:06.834 --> 00:38:09.601
is that everyone
always kind of thinks

00:38:09.601 --> 00:38:12.100
what they think
users want to hear,

00:38:12.100 --> 00:38:13.367
what they're gonna
react to,

00:38:13.367 --> 00:38:14.834
and I guarantee
you, like,

00:38:14.834 --> 00:38:17.601
if you looked
at these two messages here,

00:38:17.601 --> 00:38:18.734
half of the crowd
would say

00:38:18.734 --> 00:38:20.267
the bottom one
is the most successful,

00:38:20.267 --> 00:38:23.634
and half the crowd
would say the top.

00:38:23.634 --> 00:38:25.968
You just don't know
unless you test things.

00:38:25.968 --> 00:38:28.934
So in this example,
these two messages here

00:38:28.934 --> 00:38:31.334
had a pretty huge
difference

00:38:31.334 --> 00:38:34.100
in terms of conversion
rates.

00:38:34.100 --> 00:38:35.567
The other day I was hearing

00:38:35.567 --> 00:38:39.934
one of the top application
developers on Myspace

00:38:39.934 --> 00:38:42.167
talk about,
and he was saying,

00:38:42.167 --> 00:38:43.934
"Don't get discouraged

00:38:43.934 --> 00:38:46.534
"if your application growth
is completely flat.

00:38:46.534 --> 00:38:49.400
"Just keep tweaking things.
Little things, little things.

00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:51.901
"Keep tweaking and measuring
back and forth,

00:38:51.901 --> 00:38:53.934
"and you're gonna find
that one little thing

00:38:53.934 --> 00:38:56.701
"that actually really
starts to kind of drive

00:38:56.701 --> 00:38:58.534
"viral growth
in your application,

00:38:58.534 --> 00:39:03.434
and then hopefully
also retention."

00:39:03.434 --> 00:39:05.100
So the other thing is
it's not only gonna be

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:07.501
in the messaging that you
want to do your A/B testing,

00:39:07.501 --> 00:39:10.701
it's gonna be with what
revenue sources you're using.

00:39:10.701 --> 00:39:12.434
So you're gonna want
to do A/B testing

00:39:12.434 --> 00:39:14.834
on whether I should
use direct payment,

00:39:14.834 --> 00:39:17.701
whether I should charge people
directly with credit cards,

00:39:17.701 --> 00:39:19.300
or whether I should
present offers.

00:39:19.300 --> 00:39:20.968
And then even
within offers,

00:39:20.968 --> 00:39:24.067
you're gonna want
to be doing A/B testing

00:39:24.067 --> 00:39:27.334
to actually determine, of all
the companies that are out there

00:39:27.334 --> 00:39:29.467
that provide offer
solutions,

00:39:29.467 --> 00:39:32.133
which ones convert
the best for my audience?

00:39:32.133 --> 00:39:34.167
And that's really gonna
depend,

00:39:34.167 --> 00:39:37.133
from application
to application,

00:39:37.133 --> 00:39:40.467
which--
which offer provider--

00:39:40.467 --> 00:39:42.467
which payment provider
works best

00:39:42.467 --> 00:39:43.901
is gonna be very different

00:39:43.901 --> 00:39:48.100
because every application
has a very different audience.

00:39:48.100 --> 00:39:49.868
And a great tool is--

00:39:49.868 --> 00:39:53.868
Symmetrix has some great tools
for doing that as well.

00:39:53.868 --> 00:39:57.767
So the most
successful applications

00:39:57.767 --> 00:40:01.067
that we're seeing across
the social networks are games,

00:40:01.067 --> 00:40:02.567
particularly on Myspace.

00:40:02.567 --> 00:40:05.667
Games have done
very, very well.

00:40:05.667 --> 00:40:10.267
I think not every application
has to be a game,

00:40:10.267 --> 00:40:13.534
and not every one of you better
say, once I develop a game,

00:40:13.534 --> 00:40:16.033
but I would highly
encourage you to take a look

00:40:16.033 --> 00:40:18.868
at the design patterns that
the game providers are using

00:40:18.868 --> 00:40:21.300
because they've become
very smart about this

00:40:21.300 --> 00:40:24.334
in terms of the ways
that they get people

00:40:24.334 --> 00:40:26.734
to re-engage
with the applications

00:40:26.734 --> 00:40:30.334
by using leaderboards,
leveling up, point systems.

00:40:30.334 --> 00:40:32.534
Providing kind of
special offers that are--

00:40:32.534 --> 00:40:34.033
that are available--

00:40:34.033 --> 00:40:36.367
every day there's a new offer
that's available.

00:40:36.367 --> 00:40:39.300
These are all techniques
that any application

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:42.634
can really
take advantage of.

